Most artists I know draw for fun, so it's quite common to see them dragging their feet when it comes to commission because it's hard to motivate the brain to shift gears from drawing for fun to drawing for work. It's a heavy blow to their creativity, especially since they have a backlog of commissions to work on usually, too. It's that awkward middle-ground where, if, they were capable of pumping out finished commissions like a factory, they'd likely be the type of person to just get an industry job that pays better than what is essentially gig work instead.
Just speaking from some experience, too, from other forms of "creative" commission work I've done.
